commentBody:
@Steve L 

Mine solved in about 3/4 of Friday's time. I finished Friday's with an error and it took nearly forever to find it.

CARE TO ELABORATE and THE RAP were what took me longest today. I got CAREY pretty easily, but was afraid that STERNER just came too easily. I shouldn't have second-guessed myself! The big bottom stack filled in very easily.

@Scott Klein 

Was the group billed as "Freddie Mercury and Queen"? (Spoiler:  they weren't.)  If not, Mercury wasn't a headliner.


<a href="https://archive.org/details/live-aid-1985_202312" target="_blank">https://archive.org/details/live-aid-1985_202312</a>

@Mike 
Temper, temper.  On what do you bass your remarks?

I hope the emus like the tenor of these remarks.

@Bree 

In my first pass, I thought 16A was a clever clue for 'Marie Kondo'. ("Pitch" as in "toss out".)

The Kool-Aid Man is waaaay more clever! And now I, too, am disappointed... 



@KandB

Agree! And I see what you did there. 😂

@Erick 

Yes, but it solved so quickly and easily. 😭

I had a heart-wrenching flashback while filling it in, though!!

@Adina 
Our boy Kato weighs in at 15 lbs and sounds like he’s wearing combat boots when he runs around the house at 3am. We use the expression ONLITTLECATFEET for him constantly, but not in his presence, as he is not partial to sarcasm.
A good weekend for me, coming in at just over 50% of my average on both days. Not gloating, just praising the constructors for such excellent puzzles! 😁

@Marshall Walthew 

Antiflu kind of bothered me; seemed like a made up term.

/E-mu A-choo

@David Connell 

I blanked on the Mini’s 1A/1D until I had a few letters. I ended up solving it in 58 seconds, which is fairly typical for me on a 7 X 7 grid. 

Whenever I see a clue like 5D, I have to wonder if the clue writer has ever tried to do that “simple” trick. Per Wikipedia, it “typically takes considerable practice to learn.”

@David Connell 

The 1A/1D combo was the gimme-est gimme for me.  Imagine, besting David Connell on a music clue!!

(Even if it isn't your cup of tea, it was a big deal this year, being announced during the Super Bowl, and all that...oh, yeah, sports...)

@Mean Old Lady I winced a bit at that clue/answer, too. Descended from mountain folk in North Georgia as well, farmers and ministers.

When I first came north in my 20s, I was surprised at the assumptions made about me, personally. And about how segregated the lives were of many white liberals I met who talked a good game. Coming from Atlanta, that just seemed plain weird.

OK, rant over.

@momonjava 

About 30 years ago, my husband and I went on a long trip by train (theoretically from Austin to Chicago to Seattle to LA to Austin, spending a few days in various cities along the way.)

We bought a book of NYT puzzles edited by Eugene Maleska to help us pass the time. They were so challenging for Generation Jones solvers that I think we finished about two or three of them. (I still have the book, though. Maybe someday.)

@Lewis 

Thanks. 

That gives me some hope.

@Eric Hougland actually, I’ve only been doing crosswords for a few years now.

That said, I’ve done quite a few puzzles during that time (archives, New Yorker, local paper, etc), and I almost never “cheat” (this is the first time I’ve googled a clue in months). So I’m a little surprised I haven’t picked up AMAHL by now — especially if it appeared as recently as June!

At any rate, I’m glad to hear that is standard crosswordese. Verdict: not a Natick, and I’ll be ready for it next time :)

@Esmerelda 
Agree Doubt is a great film.

Loved this puzzle until the last letter fill, skeds seems forced.

@Emilie 

If you haven’t read too many spoilers, let this one sit for a bit. There are a few answers that some people found obscure, but I expect most of the answers, especially the long ones, are in your vocabulary. 

Congratulations on your improvement! We were all beginners at solving  once.

@Katie 

Speaking on who runs the country, there was an interesting panel concerning why there aren't more white male voices being heard any more.

The panel consisted of J. D. Vance, Lindsey Graham, Ted Cruz, Charlie Kirk, Tucker Carlson, Sean Hannity, Rick Scott, Ron DeSantis, Rubert Murdock, Charles Grassley, Sam Alito, Brett Kavanaugh, Elon Musk, and Mark Zuckerburg.

@Josh 

Have you ever heard the slang phrase “beat THE RAP”? My dictionary defines it as “to escape punishment or be acquitted of a charge.”

It might be dated. I remember it from the 1960s, though it might be even older.

@EKR 

I'm not sure I understand what you mean by the "Games format"; I haven't seen a change in how the crossword appears lately, either online or in the app.  And posting so late in the day lessens your chances of getting a helpful reply.

Nevertheless, there are settings in all versions.  Check to see what you might like to change there.

@Darren 

There was a time when I'd asked "which answers did you think were nonsensical"?

That time has passed.

@Darren 

CARE TO ELABORATE?




First of all, I hope you're trying for comic effect by saying you hated this with all your being; there are far worse things in life to hate.  As for nonsensical answers, I solved with little difficulty and failed to find more than a handful of words that might even be considered slightly nonsensical (and only if you're looking to pick nits).

@Greta Long 

Yeah, there's a lot of discussion about that below.

I'm stunned so many people know so much about Freddie Mercury.

@Mean Old Lady 

I had Biarritz as well. So proud of myself…..not.
I enjoy your comments

@Melissa 

I'd love to hear your neurologist's response if you made an appointment because "I couldn't do a NYT Friday crossword".

Probably be the biggest laugh they got all day.
